"{\"uid\": \"jamaica-gleaner.com-article-entertainment-20240726-celine-dion-makes-musical-comeback-paris-olympics-eiffel-tower\", \"text\": \"PARIS (AP) -\\u00a0Celine Dion\\u00a0made a triumphant return Friday with a very public performance: closing out the\\u00a0Paris Olympics' opening ceremony\\u00a0from the Eiffel Tower.  Nearly two years after revealing her\\u00a0stiff person syndrome diagnosis,\\u00a0Dion belted\\u00a0Edith Piaf's\\u00a0\\\"Hymne \\u00e0 l'amour\\\" (\\\"Hymn to Love\\\") as the finale of the roughly four-hour spectacle.  Her appearance had been teased for weeks, but organisers and Dion's representatives had refused to confirm\\u00a0whether she was performing.  On a page dedicated to\\u00a0Dior's contributions\\u00a0to the opening ceremony, the media guide referred to \\\"a world star, for a purely grandiose, superbly scintillating finale.\\\"  Dion had been absent from the stage since 2020, when the coronavirus pandemic forced the postponement of her tour to 2022. That tour was eventually suspended in the wake of her diagnosis.  The rare neurological disorder causes rigid muscles and painful muscle spasms, which were affecting Dion's ability to walk and sing.  In June, at the premiere of the documentary \\\"I Am: Celine Dion,\\\"\\u00a0she told The Associated Press\\u00a0that returning required therapy, \\\"physically, mentally, emotionally, vocally.\\\"  \\\"So that's why it takes a while. But absolutely why we are doing this because I am already a little bit back,\\\" she said then.  Even before the documentary's release, Dion had taken steps toward a comeback. In February, she made another surprise appearance,\\u00a0at the Grammy Awards,\\u00a0where she presented the final award of the night to a standing ovation.  Follow The Gleaner on X, formerly Twitter, and Instagram @JamaicaGleaner and on Facebook @GleanerJamaica. Send us a message on WhatsApp at 1-876-499-0169 or email us atonlinefeedback@gleanerjm.comoreditors@gleanerjm.com.  View the discussion thread.\"}"